    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-08-10T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-08-10T08:00:00-05:00" n="232"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d232">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Japan)/8–1046: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Durbrow</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="60" xml:id="d232fn1">Repeated by the Department as telegram 452, August
                        16, 1946, 8 p.m., to the Political Adviser in Japan.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-08-10T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 10, 1946—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>Received August 10—1:21 p.m.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3156. Depcir August 8, noon.<note n="61" xml:id="d232fn2">Not printed; it
                        reported telegram 351, August 1, 1946, from Tokyo, <ref target="#pg_280">p.
                            280</ref>.</note> Independent attitude displayed by Soviet military in
                    Japan seems to parallel behavior of Soviet military representatives in Italy
                    last year. <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> will recall that when such
                    behavior was brought to our attention we recommended in part that <gloss
                        target="#t_SACMED1">SACMED</gloss> take local military administrative action
                    including detention of any Soviet representatives who acted in unauthorized
                    manner (<gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss>’s 3771, November 5, 1945<note n="62"
                        xml:id="d232fn3">Not printed.</note>).</p>
                <p>Soviet Military authorities themselves strictly enforce security measures and
                    cannot logically object if we do same. So far as our view has a bearing on issue
                    we feel that <gloss target="#t_SCAP1">SCAP</gloss> would be justified in taking
                    firm measures to keep Soviet officers in bounds.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Durbrow</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
